          <div
            class="MuiBox-root css-1ldlsmb"
            id="faq-what-s-the-difference-between-eir-and-nominal-interest-rate"
          >
            <h2
              class="MuiTypography-root MuiTypography-h6 css-sylb4b-MuiTypography-root"
            >
              What's the difference between EIR and nominal interest rate?
            </h2>
            <p
              class="MuiTypography-root MuiTypography-body1 css-15njp46-MuiTypography-root"
            >
              The nominal rate is the base rate before accounting for compounding. The Effective Interest Rate (EIR) includes the effect of monthly compounding. For the same nominal rate, monthly compounding produces a slightly higher EIR. This calculator shows EIR because it's the apples-to-apples way to compare accounts — it's what you actually earn over a year.
            </p>
            <div
              class="MuiBox-root css-ah5j3r"
            >
              <span
                class="MuiTypography-root MuiTypography-caption css-1xtvbso-MuiTypography-root"
              >
                Sources
              </span>
              <ul
                class="MuiBox-root css-n1ol3p"
              >
                <li
                  class="MuiBox-root css-1itv5e3"
                >
                  <a
                    class="MuiTypography-root MuiTypography-inherit MuiLink-root MuiLink-underlineAlways css-byaapg-MuiTypography-root-MuiLink-root"
                    href="https://www.mas.gov.sg/regulation/explainers/deposit-insurance"
                    rel="noopener noreferrer"
                    target="_blank"
                  >
                    MAS — Interest Rate Disclosure Guidelines
                    <svg
                      aria-hidden="true"
                      class="MuiSvgIcon-root MuiSvgIcon-fontSizeMedium css-2e2mzl-MuiSvgIcon-root"
                      data-testid="OpenInNewIcon"
                      focusable="false"
                      viewBox="0 0 24 24"
                    >
                      <path
                        d="M19 19H5V5h7V3H5c-1.11 0-2 .9-2 2v14c0 1.1.89 2 2 2h14c1.1 0 2-.9 2-2v-7h-2zM14 3v2h3.59l-9.83 9.83 1.41 1.41L19 6.41V10h2V3z"
                      />
                    </svg>
                  </a>
                  <span
                    class="MuiTypography-root MuiTypography-caption css-1f852r2-MuiTypography-root"
                  >
                    — MAS requires banks to disclose Effective Interest Rate (EIR) to enable consumers to compare deposit products on a like-for-like basis.
                  </span>
                </li>
                <li
                  class="MuiBox-root css-1itv5e3"
                >
                  <a
                    class="MuiTypography-root MuiTypography-inherit MuiLink-root MuiLink-underlineAlways css-byaapg-MuiTypography-root-MuiLink-root"
                    href="https://www.investopedia.com/terms/e/effectiveinterest.asp"
                    rel="noopener noreferrer"
                    target="_blank"
                  >
                    Investopedia — Effective Annual Interest Rate
                    <svg
                      aria-hidden="true"
                      class="MuiSvgIcon-root MuiSvgIcon-fontSizeMedium css-2e2mzl-MuiSvgIcon-root"
                      data-testid="OpenInNewIcon"
                      focusable="false"
                      viewBox="0 0 24 24"
                    >
                      <path
                        d="M19 19H5V5h7V3H5c-1.11 0-2 .9-2 2v14c0 1.1.89 2 2 2h14c1.1 0 2-.9 2-2v-7h-2zM14 3v2h3.59l-9.83 9.83 1.41 1.41L19 6.41V10h2V3z"
                      />
                    </svg>
                  </a>
                  <span
                    class="MuiTypography-root MuiTypography-caption css-1f852r2-MuiTypography-root"
                  >
                    — The effective annual interest rate accounts for intra-year compounding. EIR = (1 + nominal_rate/n)^n − 1, where n = compounding periods per year.
                  </span>
                </li>
              </ul>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div
            class="MuiBox-root css-1ldlsmb"
            id="faq-do-i-need-to-lock-in-my-money-fixed-deposit-vs-hysa"
          >
            <h2
              class="MuiTypography-root MuiTypography-h6 css-sylb4b-MuiTypography-root"
            >
              Do I need to lock in my money (fixed deposit vs HYSA)?
            </h2>
            <p
              class="MuiTypography-root MuiTypography-body1 css-15njp46-MuiTypography-root"
            >
              No. High Yield Savings Accounts (HYSAs) are demand deposit accounts — you can withdraw your money at any time without penalty. This is the key advantage over fixed deposits, which lock your money for a set period (typically 3–24 months). The tradeoff is that fixed deposit rates are sometimes higher, especially in a falling-rate environment where they let you lock in a rate.
            </p>
            <div
              class="MuiBox-root css-ah5j3r"
            >
              <span
                class="MuiTypography-root MuiTypography-caption css-1xtvbso-MuiTypography-root"
              >
                Sources
              </span>
              <ul
                class="MuiBox-root css-n1ol3p"
              >
                <li
                  class="MuiBox-root css-1itv5e3"
                >
                  <a
                    class="MuiTypography-root MuiTypography-inherit MuiLink-root MuiLink-underlineAlways css-byaapg-MuiTypography-root-MuiLink-root"
                    href="https://www.sdic.org.sg/di_scope_of_coverage/"
                    rel="noopener noreferrer"
                    target="_blank"
                  >
                    SDIC — Scope of DI Coverage
                    <svg
                      aria-hidden="true"
                      class="MuiSvgIcon-root MuiSvgIcon-fontSizeMedium css-2e2mzl-MuiSvgIcon-root"
                      data-testid="OpenInNewIcon"
                      focusable="false"
                      viewBox="0 0 24 24"
                    >
                      <path
                        d="M19 19H5V5h7V3H5c-1.11 0-2 .9-2 2v14c0 1.1.89 2 2 2h14c1.1 0 2-.9 2-2v-7h-2zM14 3v2h3.59l-9.83 9.83 1.41 1.41L19 6.41V10h2V3z"
                      />
                    </svg>
                  </a>
                  <span
                    class="MuiTypography-root MuiTypography-caption css-1f852r2-MuiTypography-root"
                  >
                    — SDIC categorises savings accounts and fixed deposits as distinct insured deposit types. Savings accounts are demand deposits with no fixed maturity.
                  </span>
                </li>
                <li
                  class="MuiBox-root css-1itv5e3"
                >
                  <a
                    class="MuiTypography-root MuiTypography-inherit MuiLink-root MuiLink-underlineAlways css-byaapg-MuiTypography-root-MuiLink-root"
                    href="https://www.dbs.com.sg/personal/deposits/fixed-deposits"
                    rel="noopener noreferrer"
                    target="_blank"
                  >
                    DBS Fixed Deposit vs Savings
                    <svg
                      aria-hidden="true"
                      class="MuiSvgIcon-root MuiSvgIcon-fontSizeMedium css-2e2mzl-MuiSvgIcon-root"
                      data-testid="OpenInNewIcon"
